[2] Malaysia, Singapore
Date: 5 Feb 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: UK Sunday Times [edited]
<http://www.timesonline.co.uk/article/0,,2100-1471408,00.html>

Dengue fever alert in Asia
-------------------------
Travelers to Asia are being warned about a possible epidemic of
potentially fatal dengue fever, following serious outbreaks in
Malaysia and Singapore.
Malaysia recorded 13 deaths from the mosquito-borne disease in
January [2005] alone, 3 times the monthly average. The number of
confirmed cases also rose alarmingly, with 1387 reported during the
past 4 weeks. The capital, Kuala Lumpur, is one of the worst-affected
places, with the number of sufferers rising from 176 2 weeks ago to
336 last week [final week of January 2005].
Meanwhile, Singapore is experiencing its most serious outbreak of the
condition for more than 10 years. Only 4450 people fell ill with
dengue fever during the whole of 2003, yet 1145 were diagnosed last
month [January 2005] alone. Both countries have launched public
awareness campaigns, and Singapore's authorities are issuing fines to
any resident who allows mosquitoes to breed on their property.
