[4] Singapore
Date: 4 Feb 2005
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Yahoo news [edited]
<http://story.news.yahoo.com/news?tmpl=story&cid=1508&e=20&u=/afp/healthsingaporedengue>

Dengue fever hits record highs in Singapore [2004]
-----------------------------------------------
Singapore last year [2004] experienced its worst outbreak of dengue
fever in a decade, with the number of cases in the final 3 months
tripling, compared with the same period in 2003.
The number of dengue cases between October and December [2004] rose
to 3340, and the problem has crossed over into 2005, with 1145 cases
reported last month [January 2005], a spokesperson from the National
Environment Agency said on Friday [4 Feb 2005].
For all of 2004, Singapore recorded 9459 cases of dengue, almost
double the number in 2003. The National Environment Agency did not
provide figures on how many people had died in Singapore from dengue.
However, the government said in December [2004] that 3 people had
died in 2004 from the virus.
Private homes were the main breeding grounds of mosquitoes,
accounting for almost 90 percent of all breedings found last month
[January 2005], said the spokesperson. Most Singaporeans live in
apartment buildings, but many families keep potted plants in which
mosquitoes can breed. The government this month launched a crackdown
in which homeowners found with mosquitoes breeding on their premises
would be fined instantly. Penalties for construction sites are much
stiffer and can include up to 6 months in jail for those responsible.
The World Health Organization says the global prevalence of dengue
has grown dramatically in recent decades, and the disease is now
endemic in more than 100 countries.
